System Type: Dual AGN Candidate / Likely Single AGN
Selection Method: Fiber Spectra / Optical Spectroscopic Emission Line Ratios / Double-Peaked Optical Spectroscopic Emission Lines
Paper(s): Liu+2011b ; Wang+2009 ; Liu+2010a ; Tingay+2011 ; Shen+2011 ; Ge+2012 ; Fu+2012 ; Comerford+2012 ; McGurk+2015 ; Muller-Sanchez+2015
Notes: .  Tingay+ find no evidence of double radio cores in VLBA imaging.  Shen+2011 attribute the double-peaked lines to NLR kinematics. Only a single nucleus is resolved in near-IR imaging and the spatial offset observed between the two velocity components of the emission lines is larger than >0.6. If the double-peaks were due to two NLRs from dual AGNs there should be two nuclei visible in the imaging. No companion within 3 arcseconds. Comerford+ examined long slit spectra of this target. Two spatially distinct emission peaks observed. No companion within 3 arcseconds.Muller-Sanchez+2015 find that the origin of the double-peaked emission is still ambiguous. AGN 1 is a double-peaked AGN.

Severgnini rule out strong radio jets but cannot rule out faint radio jets. They note that the velocity offsets are fully consistent with the rotation velocities measured in nearby galaxies and therefore the offsets could be explained by kinematics in a single NLR. They detect X-ray flux variability (periodicity of ~25 months) and argue it is intrinsic flux variations rather than varying obscuration. They also report a tentive double-peaked iron line due either to rational in an accretiondisk or a binary AGN. Under the binary hypothesis the double peaked optical lines would be due to rotationin the galaxy and not the binary. By measuring the power spectrum of this object Liu+2020 rejected the 25 month periodicity that Severgnini found. Severgnini did not fit the power spectrum. This object was excluded from the Serafinelli+ due to the g-test selection criteria. Serafinelli+ show the power spectrum density is consistent with white noise but when they perform a weighted sinusoid fit they find a period of ~26.3 months. Whenthey consider the 123 month data they find a period of 26.0 months and claim to reject the null at 3.4sigma. This period is consistent with that proposed by Severgnini+.

Liu+ resolve two stellar bulges and two NLRs in this system using HST. The HST data disfavor a biconical outflow scenario and they favor a dual AGN scenario; given the separation they cannot rule out a single AGN ionizing both nuclei. Liu+ finds the separation to be slightly smaller for the OIII emitting regions than the host stellar bulges.

System Type: Dual AGN Candidate / Binary AGN Candidate
Notes: -99AGN 1 selected as a candidate binary based on periodicity.

Hutsemekers+ find in their spectropolarimetric obs that the BAL profiles are nearly identical between the two spectra. This strongly suppoprts the notion of a lens rather than a binary given how unlikely it is that to find two similar absorbers in the two AGNs. Microlensing appears to show two sources of continuum. An intervening absorption line system is observed around z=1 in both images but with different intensities. This absorption line system hints at the presence of a lens galaxy.
. Nearly identical quasars and no lens galaxy detected.

Velocity Shifts between Narrow and Broad Lines
Paper(s): Tsalmantza+2011 ; Decarli+2013 ; Lusso+2014 ; Liu+2014 ; Eracleous+2012 ; Runnoe+2015 ; Runnoe+2017 ; Nguyen+2020
Notes: Decarli+ find most objects do not undergo significant profile or flux variation. Lusso+ fit the SEDs to search for evidence of peculiar properties that could be consistent with the recoil hypothesis. In a scenario where the recoils displaced from the center of the galaxy and has left the torus behind the AGN should show a deficit of 12um emission. They find that all objects in the sample (with the possible exception of J1154) exhibit a significant amount of 12um emission in contrast to the recoil scenario.

Paper(s): Wang+2009 ; Ge+2012 ; Comerford+2012 ; Severgnini+2018 ; Liu+2020 ; Serafinelli+2020
Notes: Comerford+ examined long slit spectra of this target. Two spatially distinct emission peaks observed.Severgnini rule out strong radio jets but cannot rule out faint radio jets. They note that the velocity offsets are fully consistent with the rotation velocities measured in nearby galaxies and therefore the offsets could be explained by kinematics in a single NLR. They detect X-ray flux variability (periodicity of ~25 months) and argue it is intrinsic flux variations rather than varying obscuration. They also report a tentive double-peaked iron line due either to rational in an accretiondisk or a binary AGN. Under the binary hypothesis the double peaked optical lines would be due to rotationin the galaxy and not the binary. By measuring the power spectrum of this object Liu+2020 rejected the 25 month periodicity that Severgnini found. Severgnini did not fit the power spectrum. This object was excluded from the Serafinelli+ due to the g-test selection criteria. Serafinelli+ show the power spectrum density is consistent with white noise but when they perform a weighted sinusoid fit they find a period of ~26.3 months. Whenthey consider the 123 month data they find a period of 26.0 months and claim to reject the null at 3.4sigma. This period is consistent with that proposed by Severgnini+.

No companion within 3 arcseconds. Comerford+2018 studied the kinematics that give rise to the double-peaks. Song+2020 examined a subsample of the double-peaked objects in Smith+2010 but did not include a table specifying the objects. We include a reference to all of them for now. Song+ disfavor a binary hypothesis.

Shen+2011 find only a single resolved nucleus in near-IR imaging but the velocity separation of the emission lines are spatially offset by <0.4 which is below the resolution limit of the near-IR imaging. These could be single AGNs or closer dual AGNs. Angular separation is derived from the separation observed between the velocity separated lines in the slit spectrum.  Comerford+ examined long slit spectra of this target. Two spatially distinct emission peaks observed. Comerford+2018 studied the kinematics that give rise to the double-peaks.

Comerford+ examined long slit spectra of this target. Two spatially distinct emission peaks observed. Comerford+2012 consider this a strong dual AGN candidate. Double optical emission line peaks observed oriented along the plane of the galaxy.Muller-Sanchez+2015 find that the origin of the double-peaked lines is likely an jet-driven outflow.

Paper(s): Wang+2009 ; Ge+2012 ; Comerford+2012 ; Severgnini+2018 ; Liu+2020 ; Serafinelli+2020
Notes: Comerford+ examined long slit spectra of this target. Two spatially distinct emission peaks observed.Severgnini rule out strong radio jets but cannot rule out faint radio jets. They note that the velocity offsets are fully consistent with the rotation velocities measured in nearby galaxies and therefore the offsets could be explained by kinematics in a single NLR. They detect X-ray flux variability (periodicity of ~25 months) and argue it is intrinsic flux variations rather than varying obscuration. They also report a tentive double-peaked iron line due either to rational in an accretiondisk or a binary AGN. Under the binary hypothesis the double peaked optical lines would be due to rotationin the galaxy and not the binary. By measuring the power spectrum of this object Liu+2020 rejected the 25 month periodicity that Severgnini found. Severgnini did not fit the power spectrum. This object was excluded from the Serafinelli+ due to the g-test selection criteria. Serafinelli+ show the power spectrum density is consistent with white noise but when they perform a weighted sinusoid fit they find a period of ~26.3 months. Whenthey consider the 123 month data they find a period of 26.0 months and claim to reject the null at 3.4sigma. This period is consistent with that proposed by Severgnini+.

Paper(s): Weedman+1982 ; Subramanian+1984 ; Weir+1991 ; Duncan+1991 ; Steidel+1991 ; Bonnet+1993 ; Fischer+1994 ; Mellier+1994 ; Patnaik+1996 ; Dolan+1996 ; Small+1997 ; Green+2002
Notes: No X-ray evidence for a foreground lensing cluster found by Green+2002 and no lens identified; X-ray continua are found to be incompatible as are the optical to X-ray flux ratios; the optical spectral similarities remains a mystery. Coordinates from Simbad.

Confirmation Method: Slitless Optical Spectroscopy / Optical Slit Spectroscopy / Near-IR Imaging / Optical Imaging
Notes: Spectra have striking similarities but no evidence for a lensing cluster of galaxy even in HST imaging. Coordinates from Simbad.
Coordinates from Simbad. Redshifts pulled from Hudson+2006.

Confirmation Method: Radio Imaging / Optical Imaging / Narrow-band Optical Imaging / Optical Slit Spectroscopy / IFU Optical Imaging / IFU Optical Spectroscopy
Notes: Possible QSO-AGN pair at similar redshifts but note the redshift differences as these might be further away than originally thought ; Hu+1987 call into question interepretation and conclude that companion is likely just an ionized gas cloud. Coordinates come from Simbad. Husband+2015 describe the system as a quasar and an AGN companion. Should check and see if there any additional papers confirming the redshifts. Probably need to go back and cite Bremer and Johnstone+1995. Check with Barry.

Confirmation Method: Optical Imaging / Grating Optical Spectroscopy / Radio Imaging
Notes: Using the same coordinates because secondary coordinates not specified. Coordinates come from Simbad. Check with Barry.

Selection Method: Optical Spectroscopy / Double-Peaked Optical Spectroscopic Emission Lines
Paper(s): Peterson+1987 ; Sergeev+1997 ; Sergeev+2007 ; Li+2016; Bon+2016 ; Ili+2017
Notes: Distinct BLR emitting regions can be plausibly explained via a dual AGN scenario. Not conclusive at this point. Redshift adopted from Simbad. Sergeev+97 looked at OIII wings and I'm not sure how relevant this paper is. Sergeev+07 looked at 30 years of and fonud no evidence of Hbeta line and continuum variability except for in 1972-1988; no obvious support for binary scenario. Both Bon+ and Li+ claim periodicity in this object based on long baseline observations (several decades); Bon+ suggests the periodicity could be due to a stellar mass body impacting the accretion disk of the SMBH; Li+ propose a binary SMBH model can explain the periodicity of 14 years (but only ~2 cycles have been observed). Ilic+2017 really only brings this up in the context of the Li+ result and how a binary could affect the mass measurements from reverberation mapping.

Confirmation Method: Optical Imaging / Radio Imaging / Optical Spectroscopy
Notes: Separation of optical sources AB_opt and C is 4.8 arcsec but separation of radio sources is roughly 5.9 arcsec. Coordinates come from Simbad (and originally from SDSS). Check with Barry.

Selection Method: Double-Peaked Optical Spectroscopic Emission Lines / Optical Spectroscopy
Paper(s): Halpern+1988 ; Miller+1990 ; Halpern+1992 ; Eracleous+1997 ; Gezari+2007 ; Liu+2016 ; Doan+2020
Notes: Halpern+1988 test binary hypothesis based on offset broad emission line but no firm conclusion made. Other papers conclude that binary hypothesis can be ruled out. Coordinates from Simbad. Redshift from Ned agrees with Simbad to 3 decimal points. Eracleous+ place lower limit of 10^10 for the mass of the SMBHs in the binary scenario. The constraints they place argue against the binary hypothesis. Gezari+ argue against a binary hypothesis. Liu+2016 argues the binary hypothesis is incompatible with data spanning several decades (either the periods are longer than 20 years or other mechanisms give rise to the observed emission line velocity changes) and provides additional arguments against the binary hypothesis outside of the spectroscopic analysis. Doan+ argue strongly against binary hypothesis based on multiple arguments including estimates on the lower limit on the mass of the putative binary.

Selection Method: Double-Peaked Optical Spectroscopic Emission Lines / Optical Spectroscopy
Notes: Halpern+ search for orbital motion but do not find evidence. Eracleous+ argue against a binary hypothesis. Gezari+ argue against a binary hypothesis. No regular variability observed. Liu+2016 argues the binary hypothesis is incompatible with data spanning several decades (either the periods are longer than 20 years or other mechanisms give rise to the observed emission line velocity changes) and provides additional arguments against the binary hypothesis outside of the spectroscopic analysis. Doan+ estimated lower limits on the mass of the putative binary and argues against the binary hypothesis in this system for multiple reasons.
Proposed as a SMBH binary with separation ~0.1pc. Sandrinelli+2016 report peaks at ~435 days in NIR bands and ~410 days in gamma rays. Rieger+007 list it in their table of binayr candidates.

Confirmation Method: Slitless Optical Spectroscopy / Optical Slit Spectroscopy / Optical Imaging / Near-IR Imaging
Notes: Redshifts from Crampton+1988 but Dinshaw+1994 quote slightly different redshifts. Coordinates from simbad.

Confirmation Method: CCD Photometry / Spectroscopy / X-ray Spectroscopy and Imaging
Paper(s): Mazzarella+1988 ; Brassington+2007 ; Wang+2010 ; Mazzarella+2012 ; Torres-Alba+2018 ; Iwasawa+2020
Notes: See earlier papers by Petrosian+1980 Osterbrock+1983 and Kollatschny+1984 about optical spectroscopy. Iwasawa+ confirm via NuSTAR that the AGN in the SW nucleus is Compton thick in agreement with that inferred from earlier Chandra observations. Brassington+ was first to suggest presence of X-ray AGNs though results were not firm. Mazzarrella+ confirmed Chandra sources and was first to propose that SW source was Compton-thick and the primary driver of the iron line seen in XMM imaging and spectra while the northern LINER nucleus was a a less obscured AGN.

Despite the original suspicion that this was a gravitational lens candidate Mthur+2003 argue against the lens interpretation and find that the X-ray properties of the sources are incompatible with one another and that the X-ray emission from the potential foreground cluster is unlikely to be the long soughtafter foreground lens ; Aldrcroft confirm many of Mathur's findings but argues that the lens interpretation cannot be completely ruled out. Coordinates from simbad.

Confirmation Method: Optical Imaging / Slit Optical Spectroscopy / Near-IR Imaging
Notes: Considered a lens candidate by Hewett+89 but Faure+2003 argue based on VLT and HST data that the system is unlikely to be a lens but rather is a true binary ; note that 1429-008 from Hewett+89 is 1429-0053 from Faure+2003. Shapovalova+2001 dismiss the binary hypothesis and find that the emission can be modeled by an inclined accretion disk. Eracleous+ also dismissed the binary hypothesis due to the fact that the velocity shifts observed by Gaskell+ do not follow the extrapolation of the binary model using data points from a longer baseline. They also observe that the trend in velocity of the red peak of the Halpha line is also not consistent with orbital models. Gezari+ also argue against binary and find no correlation between the coherent regions of the profile that vary across decades. Liu+2016 argues the binary hypothesis is incompatible with data spanning several decades (either the periods are longer than 20 years or other mechanisms give rise to the observed emission line velocity changes) and provides additional arguments against the binary hypothesis outside of the spectroscopic analysis. Doan+ strongly disfavor binary hypothesis based on multiple tests including estimates on the lower mass limit for the putative binary. Krause+ claims jet precession. Not sure where the separation here comes from.

Paper(s): Boroson+2009 ; Chornock+2009 ; Wrobel+2009 ; Lauer+2009 ; Decarli+2009 ; Tang+2009 ; Chornock+2010 ; Gaskell+2010 ; Bondi+2010
Notes: Boroson+ originally identify this as a binary candidate while later works suggest a dual hypothesis (Decarli+ and Wrobel+). Chornock argue that it is an unusual double peak emitter. While there is a double optical K-band and radio sources (shown by Wrobel+ Decarli+ and Lauer+) Lauer+ show that the dual AGN hypothesis is not consistent with the data. While they do not rule out the binary hypothesis they do state that the Double-Peaked scenario could be true. Chornock+2010 argue in favor again of the Double-Peaked emitter hypothesis. They show the broad emission components arise from the same region and no velocity shifts are observed in the spectra across ~1 year. Chornock+ vannot conclusively rule out binary but prefer Double-Peaked emitter. Gaskell+ also argues in favor of the Double-Peaked emitter hypothesis. Coordinates drawn from the naming convention but we should consider changing these to the positions of the radio nuclei. Bondi+ show that there do exist two compact radio nuclei in J1536 as well as in the companion 0.97'' away confirming the presnce of two AGNs in the vicinity. They bring up that the Chornock conclusion was based on data obtained in seeing conditions worse than the angular separation of the two so the conclusion about spatially coincident broad lines may not be true. While Bondi do not make any firm conclusions on the nature of J1536 they do clearly confirm the VLA-A and VLA-B sources detected by Wrobel+ with a separation 0.97'' or ~5.1kpc separation. System Type: Dual AGN Candidate / AGN Recoil Candidate
Selection Method: X-Shaped Radio Source / X-ray Imaging / X-ray Spectroscopy
Paper(s): Murgia+2001 ; Merritt+2002 ; Gopal-Krishna+2003 ; Zier+2005 ; Lal+2007 ; Hodges-Kluck+2012
Notes: Redshift from NED and coordinates are from Murgia+. Murgia+ detects two radio cores with VLA 1.4 GHz imaging (and possible 4.8 GHz as well) coincident with the two dumbell components in HST imaging. Separation of 7.1''. I think the radio sources have inverted and flat radio spectra? Merritt+ Gobal-Krishna+ and Zier+ explain the X-shaped radio morphology in terms of a spin-flip after a SMBH merger (hence this is a dual AGN candidate and an AGN recoil candidate). Hodges-Kluck+ report the presence of X-ray sources in both dumbbell components. Core 1 has a power law component and an AGN is favored. In core 2 there is no clear nuclear point source but they do find a power law frozen at Gamma=2 aids the fit. Hard emission could arise from XRBs but they cannot rule out an AGN in core 2 due to the detected radio core at ~1 GHz. This is cross listed as a dual AGN candidate and a recoil candidate.

Notes: Shapovalova+ claim multiple periodicities but one of these has no physical explanation while another is based on basically one cycle. Ilic+ brings up results from Shapovalova+ and Ronbinson+ but does not appear to expand upon them; they find the source shows almost no variability.

Roland+2013 and Qian+2013 find evidence for jet precession after tracking motion of superluminal components. Qian+2019 suggests a double jet model and that there are two prcessing jets. Coordinates and redshift from Simbad. Sandrinelli2016 report peaks at ~910 days. This is considered one of the three most convincingly periodic sources. They also report a peak around ~260 days.

Selection Method: Radio Morphology+Helical Model or Structure / Quasi-Periodicity
Paper(s): Conway+1995 ; Villata+1999 ; Rieger+2000 ; Rieger+2003 ; Rieger+2007 ; Bhatta+2019
Notes: Conway+ applied hydrodynamic models to the misaligned jet components in Mrk 501 and found it coud be consistent with a helical jet driven by a SMBH binary. Mrk 501 shows a roughly 79 deg twist in the PA of the jet between the pc and kpc scales. They argue this is due to the orbital motion of the binary. Villata+ argue this precession structure is due to the black hole spin axis and so the helical structure is driven by one of the black holes in the binary. Bhatta+ report a 332 day QPO in this system (that persists for up to 7 cycles) and could be driven by a SMBH (among other things). Rieger+07 lists it in their table of binary candidates.

Paper(s): Rieger+2010 ; Sandrinelli+2014 ; Zhang+2014 ; Sandrinelli+2016 ; Zhang+2017 ; Sandrinelli+2018 ; Covino+2019
Notes: Reiger+ discuss outburst activity in 2006 and the Quasi-Periodicity in the context of a SMBH ; Sandrinelli+2014 rreport >=3mag variability ; Sandrinelli+ report statistically significant Quasi-Periodicity using a method recommended by Vaughan+; confirms periodicity reported by Sandrinelli+2014. Zhang+ reports Quasi-Periodicity in 35 year light curves and variation in color. Sandrinelli+2016 report a peak at about 315 days confirming the previously reported peak by Sandrinelli+2014. They also report peaks around 453 days and 151 days. Zhang+2017 find a 4.9sigma significance Quasi-Periodicity in the gamma ray flux with period of ~640 days which si consistent with Sandrinelli+. Covino+ argue that that there is no strong case for year-long quasi-periodicities and the power spectrum is consistent with being generated by red noise.

Confirmation Method: Optical Imaging / X-ray Imaging / X-ray Spectroscopy / Slit Optical Spectroscopy / Fiber Spectroscopy / Optical Spectroscopic Emission Line Ratios / Offset Optical Spectroscopic Emission Lines / Radio Imaging
Paper(s): Comerford+2009b; Civano+2010; Civano+2012; Blecha+2013; Lanzuisi+2013; Wrobel+2014; Wrobel+2014
Notes: Coordinates from the COSMOS naming convention. Separation from Civano+2010. Redshift from Civano+2010. Comerford argues in favor of a dual AGN in this system; Civano+10 argues that the system could be described by a recoiling SMBH or a dual AGN (Type I/Type II) with the Type I AGN recoiling. Blecha+13 finds the system can also be described using the recoiling / dual AGN+recoiling hypothesis. Ciavno+2012 uses Chandra HRC and finds only one of optical nuclei is responsible for whole X-ray unobscured; one of the nuclei is more consistent with a SF region and so they favor the GW recoil scenario rather than a dual AGN scenario; but a scenario involving a heavily obscured nucleus in the second nucleus cannot be fully ruled out. Lanzuisi+ analyzes the XMM spectrum to investigate the P-Cygni profile. Wrobel+14 finds no radio emission at the positions of the two nuclei; the NW nucleear properties are consistent with a CT AGN; they argue that CID-42 is either a dual AGN or a Type II CT AGN and a recoiling AGN where the recoiling AGN was ejected due to a triple SMBH interaction. NO ONE MENTIONS THE COORDINATES FOR DISTINCT NUCLEI. COORDINATES ARE FOR THE SYSTEM AS FAR BRIGHTNESS MEASUREMENTS; THESE ARE NOT FOR DISTINCT NUCLEI YET.

Notes: Two compact emitting regions identified: N1 coincident with continuum peak and the radio core and N2 is offset by 1.2''. Both are optically AGNs based on emission line ratios but N2 shows stronger [OIII]. Thus N2 is a possible secondary nucleus with an AGN. No compact radio source coincides with N2 so it is likely radio quiet and obscured given the lack of broad lines. No counterpart to N2 is seen with Chandra eMERLIN or HST (with the exception of HST F606W which shows an elongated feature coincident with N2). Thus they cannot rule out that N2 is a bright knot of emission caused by a jet-cloud interaction. They disfavor this scenario because (1) such interactions usually produce broad lines (2) N2 is not located along th jet axis but along an edge of the eastern lobe (3) the ionization structure at N2's location would be a fortuitous spatial coincidence and (4) N2 has a very high line luminosity (~10^42 erg s^-1). No coordinates are provided nor are distinct redshifts provided. Velocity offset measured from line peaks is roughly 200 km s^-1.

Spingola+ detect proper motion of the lens images and attribute it to motion of the source and not the lens. Two scenarios are proposed to explain the observed proper motion of the lens images: (1) a single AGN scenario where the proper motion is due to knots moving along a jet or (2) the magnified object is a dual radio-loud AGN separated by ~175 pc in projection and both have core-jet morphologies. The latter scenario is driven mostly by the motion of the flat-spectrum radio components. Additional observations are needed. They remark in the paper that a single AGN scenario may not be compatible with the observations. Coordinates of radio components are given relative to the lens; for now I am only listing the coordinates from NED.

Notes: Sun+ show that the QSO is not actually spatially offset from its host but that ther is a companion galaxy nearby. Companion could shows Seyfert-like emission but they cannot rule out the case of an EELR or ionization by the nearby QSO. Distance between the centers of the galaxies found to be 3.0'' for hte 3 D spectra. We adopt that for the separation. Radial velocity difference quoted as 120 km per s. Sun+ argue that the QSO is indeed recoiling w/ radial velocity ~1400 km per s and is accompanied by a circular disk that emits the observed double peaks. Other scenarios involve a circular disk with spiral emissivity perturbations and emissions from bipolar outflow. If the companion does in fact host its own AGN rather than being ionized by the primary QSO or overlaps with the EELR of the primary QSO then this system would consistute a dual AGN as well. Coordinates are not provided for either the primary QSO or the nucleus of the companion. Need to come back and mark the long-slit and optical imaging as analysis methods.

Confirmation Method: Long-Slit Optical Spectroscopy / IFU Optical Spectroscopy / Optical Imaging / Radio Imaging
Notes: Kim+2015 and +2017 seemed to use Chandra imaging ptical spectroscopy and imaging and UV and radio imaging to determine ths secondary source is a ULX and that it shares many properties commonly seen in LLAGNs. It has UV optical X-ray and radio counterparts. They rule out a foreground or background AGN scenario. Optical spectra suggest photoionization by an accretion powered source and the emission lines palce the emitting region within NGC 5252. Kim+2015 cannot rule out that the primary nucleus is responsible for the ionization seen but they argue that the photionization is more likely due to the ULX and that the ULX hosts an IMBH and argue that it likely originated from a dwarf galaxy that was accreted. Kim+2017 find that the OIII emission line ratios peak near the position of the ULX (and without any change in electron density or enhanced metallicity in the vicinity of the ULX implies the ULX is the power source) and they find evidence of rotation around the ULX position. In fact they find that the gas around the ULX has significantly lower Halpha/[NII] than the main galaxy and thus the metallicity is lower. This again agrees with the idea that this ULX originated from a low metallicity low mass galaxy. These observations reaffirm that the background QSO scenario is unlikely. Yang+ detect the radio source in EVN observations and report that it has a high brightness temperature a partially optically thick radio spectrum and a relatively stable luminosity and identify the source as a radio core of the offnuclear object. The radio structure at 1.66 GHz is compact (parsec-scale) and has a flat spectrum. They argue the offnuclear source is a SMBH and a LLAGN. However Mezcua+ examined follow-up VLBA imaging that resolve the radio core into two components separated by 2.9mas at 4.4 GHz but a single unresolved source is identified at 7.6 GHz. Mezcua+ identify the western source as the core and the eastern source as a jet. Rather than a SMBH Mezcua+ argue that the ULX hosts an IMBH and that it originated in a compact dwarf galaxy that was accreted by NGC 5252.

VLBI observations reveal a one sided long curved jet. Brightest portion of the radio jet could be a core-jet structure or jet knot; the coordinates for this are used a A+B position. Another source (X) resides to the north. X has a high brightness temp and flat spectrum consistent with being the optically thick base of a jet. The nature of this source is uncertain and needs further attention. If it is a secondary SMBH this would be a binary. However this secondary SMBH could not explain the precession of the jet nor can it account for the double-peaked lines. These latter two phenomenon are likely caused by a jet-NLR interaction. Notes: 5.8 arcsec offset from nucleus of dwarf galaxy (Mrk 177 at 28.9 Mpc away). Very unusual source; the eission is localized to an off nuclear position and within ~12pc based on K band imaging and <22pc based on Pa-beta with colors consistent with local quasars. SII and OI optical diagnostics imply Seyfert emission but OIII diagnostic implies HII region. Broad emission lines are observed but with no velocity offset (so if it is recoiling SMBH the velocity is transverse to the LOS). The source persists for ~63 years and shows variability in brightness but shows no significant color evolution. Broad Fe II and broad NIR Ca II lines are present as well as a statistically significant blue power law continuum with no detected host absorption lines. Also shows relatively constant UV luminosity. However rapid drop in luminosity in 2002-2003 narrow Fe II and Ca II lines are difficult to reconcile with AGN. This system is likely a recoiling AGN OR an eruptive LBV star outbursting for decades before resulting in a Type IIn SN.

Notes: Iwasawa+2011 argue that the obscured AGN detected via Chandra arises from the southern nucleus. They note an extension toward the north. U+2013 examined this system with Keck and find the nucleus is resolved into three components: N SW and SE. They find a rotating gaseous disk in the N component; the enclosed gas suggests the presence of a SMBH at the center. They identify bright K' and H-band continua along with the [Si VI] coronal line in the SW component and argue that previously identified obscured AGN likely resides in the SW component. They suggest the N AGN may be heavily obscured. Imanishi+ note that both nuclei are selected as IR AGNs using their near-IR color criteria. Iwasawa+2018 return to this with NuSTAR; when fitting the data with an obscured single power law they noticed the resulting power law index remained remarkably hard. Because of this they tested a two AGN modelw here both are heavily obscured; the model describes the data well as is comparable to if not a better fit than the single AGN model. They find the N source to be CT and the SW source to be obscured with 2e+23 cm-2. They also argue that a two AGN scenario is supported by the observed variability above and below 10 keV. They cannot rule out a single X-ray scenario but the introduce of a second AGN does offer a simpler explanation for the observed spectral hardness and is consistent with what U+2013 found. COORDINATES AND REDSHIFTS ARE NOT UNIQUE. Barrows+ selected this as an offset AGN but it is a dual AGN.
